>We used to get all the pre-released metal stuff from this independent record shop. They hated that shit, so they gave it all to us. Gave us a good laugh, so we wrote them a letter, like, “Venom, this is really, really funny. Cheered us up endlessly, here’s our record.” What I’m going to tell you now is a bit controversial. I got a letter, literally from Abaddon, and he said explicitly: “Thanks man, for the letter. We’ll rip you off.” Next thing you know, Black Metal came out. I've been producing since December 2013 and I wouldn't describe myself as "good" at all, and I'm certainly not bored. I would say I know how to do this skill to a satisfactory level that never stops having room for improvement, as the world of music is infinite. Changing DAWs seems utterly pointless, since it is just slowing down the process of getting the exact same end product. Anyone feeling bored/plateaud should pick an important skill and really develop it. For me, it was singing. Being able to sing opened some doors for me, because I now had the option to record myself anytime whenever something popped into my head, and then recreate it later. Another important thing is to be able to play the piano to some degree so you can learn to play different kinds of music and incorporate their composition style into your own to just the right extent that you create something new and exciting to work on.

I think you should try to meet people where they are. When you make chords you probably mostly use diatonic triads of the 12 tone equal temperament system in common cadences and voicings, just like everyone else. There are ways to subvert norms and cliches and introduce people to other sounds, but it doesn't involve wholesale avoidance of those norms. You can more effectively introduce people to the sounds you want them to hear by offering them music that is 80% the sounds they are used to and 20% other sounds you want them to hear. Then mix that resulting sound with 20% other sounds you want people to hear. And so on and so forth.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
In regards to mixing, the foundation is sound selection. Especially your kick and bass need to work together. I've lost hours trying to get my kick sound good with EQ, sidechaining, compressing... but all I needed to do is simply choose another kick with a better transient. 80% of your "mixing" should be the volume fader. If you get sounds work together by simply adjusting the volume fader you need to decide which sound you should replace. If your kick cuts through the bass without any processing you have chosen the right one. The processing itself takes it from 8/10 to 10/10.

Drum sounds are repetitive as fuck, especially when you listen to the current trap rap and drill music. It's like all producers are sharing the same 5 drum kits. Creating your own is part of establishing your own style. Those drums sounds could be based on commonly used sounds but with your personal processing. You created a great snare for one of your tracks? Save it. Layered a great kick? Save it. This is how you end up with your personal drum kit, that sounds like you. My drum sounds are all my own, but it took me years to create my own library sampling real drum sounds from old records. I am currently sampling some 70s Russian progressive rock record that I would like to use for deep house.

What I do is start with the kick. I'll get my kick to sound just like I want it and peak at -12 db. This is my fixed point. I never touch the fader of the kick again. Everything else will get mixed around my kick as the anchor. At because it is the loudest element of my tracks I have my gain staging covered because everything else will be mixed lower in volume and I have more than enough headroom going into the master.

sounds very Clams Casino. however your drums are too weak. I'm gonna assume FL Studio here. get a break sample, and fruity slicex it. get some snappier snares, some chunkier kicks. check out Clams Casino (if you don't already know) for the type of drums that'd work well for this style.

your bass should be cutting through a bit more. it's sitting very far in the back of the mix. widen it out, bring it a bit more forward. bass should be a really solid foundation for everything else, not too thin. things are really hard to make out in general. It's pretty atmospheric, lots of pads and glittery sounds, but you need to EQ them better. they're all blending together in the mix. you should be able to hear every detail from all your sounds more, and if you have unwanted bass or high ends (unwanted bass in your pads for example), then eq that shit out.

Tenderness is a rare emotion in the world of music. Why?

Ever since the dawn of the doctrine of affect, the painting of emotions in music has been constantly refined, and in the so-called romantic composers we have no difficulty in recognising such refined emotions as jealousy or cruelty, the thirst for love or indifference.

Everything Handel has written has an air of urgency about it. But unlike Mozart, this does not come at all from being forced into stopgaps, missing the obvious or otherwise taking shortcuts that he would have regretted in retrospect if he had given them a thought.

No, the urgency is of the kind of that in a factory during a boom. G. F. Handel Inc. The ingenious but unreliable staff of neurons throwing out bursts of suggestions — which the supervisor, the controller, scrutinizes with a gaze as accustomed as it is unblinking. In Handel's music there is only room for the effective. The sublime, before which his colleague J. S. Bach shows such a peculiar interest, can give him nothing. Handel is interested only in the human. And the most human of all is the power of speech - that remarkable gift of being able to put one's point across in successive sounds. Pauses, accents, ritardandi, accelererandi. Bach says it all at once — when his music has ended, you are no wiser than you were a moment ago — quite the opposite. Bach's music is for angels, who can see beyond the corners of time. It could just as well be played backwards — which, of course, this man of God could not fail to do from time to time. Handel is a man of men. He can only think ahead.

Handel learns the arts in order to use them for a specific purpose - entertainment. Tension and relaxation. Secrets revealed, events unfolding. That's why he wrote operas while Bach wrote masses and passions. The texts Bach composed contain no surprises, there is drama, but not suspense. Handel writes for the voice — Bach writes for the voice as an instrument. Bach teaches the arts for their own sake — they too are created by God, and are therefore on an equal footing with man. Handel uses the arts as a means.

Bach and Handel — the secrets of art and the art of secrets.

There are plenty histories of music you can read. There's the Oxford History of Western Music (this is the book by Taruskin that the other Anon mentioned), the Cambridge History of Music, or Norton's Western Music in Context. Each of these is 5-7 volumes, starting from the middle ages or what little music we have from antiquity, and continuing to the present day. There's also a one-volume History of Western Music by Burkholder, Grout, and Palisca, if you want something shorter. The are some good period-specific books like Manfred Bukofzer's Music in the Baroque Era or Charles Rosen's The Classical Style and The Romantic Generation. If you want something really basic, but that also includes musical excerpts, there's the lecture series How to Listen to and Understand Great Music from the Teaching Company, a link to a torrent download of which you can find in the pastebin in the OP of this thread. There's lots of other stuff you can read as well if you just search around. Hope this helps.

On the front cover of Ralph Vaughan Willams' Fifth Symphony we read an unexpected dedication: 'Without permission but with sincere flattery to Jean Sibelius, whose example is worthy of imitation'.

Imitation? No one familiar with these names could be anything but surprised. The superficial similarities that a feeble mind immediately sees - proximity to folk music, romanticism of nature (whatever that is), distance from contemporary iconoclastic movements, et cetera - fall by the wayside alongside the differences that an attentive ear catches. There is hardly any affinity of spirit - where Sibelius is restless and restless, Vaughan Williams's music (with a few exceptions, like the Fourth Symphony) is instead suffused with a bottomless calm; where Vaughan Williams's tonal language is translucent, Sibelius's is in turn murky. But if you listen more deeply, there is actually a rarely noticed similarity: namely, in their relationships to time. Two examples: their respective Symphonies No. 5.

The classical sonata form — with which neither of them broke entirely — famously presents the material in a 'logical', or rather pedagogical, form. First the theme in its original form, which is the same as its final form, then the second (third, fourth) theme, development, repetition of all of it, variations and then conclusion with the theme in its first form. Sibelius completely turns his back on this pedagogical order in his Fifth Symphony, instead beginning with variations, drafts, sudden turns, long digressions without a clear basis, until finally the main theme (we now understand) thunders in its perfection and then gives way to a short interlude that seamlessly leads into the next movement. Dynamic evolution - not static exposition. This has of course been pointed out before.

(The lack of "logic" (for lack of a better word) prompted Theodor Adorno to comment "[I]f Sibelius is good, this nullifies long-established criteria of musical quality from Bach to Schoenberg [...]", and René Leibowitz to famously declare Sibelius "the worst composer in the world".)

Instead, Vaughan Williams' music often reflects the historical evolution of music. From the first steps of the simplest bone flute to the era of the great orchestra. First pentatonic, then the sixth note fills in, then the seventh. Then polytonality and finally chromaticism. Sibelius's music mimics another evolution: first a primordial cell, which then divides to finally form a distinct organism. None of these schemata are as simple as I describe them, of course — if they were, I wouldn't write about them. But they can be found at the underwater level. (Or perhaps rather: they become crystal clear when viewed correctly; as a geometric figure that is only understood when you realise that it is three dimensions projected onto two.)

/.../

(At this point, a decade after the final fading of musical ideologies, it may well be added that the music that at the turn of the last century was considered the music of the future — and whose thought world is responsible for the attacks cited above — is fading further into the margins, while the names Vaughan Williams and Sibelius are increasingly appearing on concert programmes and in radio schedules. Also an evolution.)

When we listen to music in its infancy - Schoenberg's piano pieces before he formalised the twelve-tone technique, for example — we can't escape the underlying narrative. We know what is to come, and we experience something akin to movement; like watching a child take its first steps. The grave-voice that the music wants to give the impression of, that of having entered a new path, was only possible to hear if you were contemporary. Now we see it in a mirror of laughter.

When we listen to music that is on, if not exactly the deathbed, then on the sickbed — Strauss's Elektra, for example — history makes us perceive a breakdown; where Strauss thought he was achieving perfection, we hear decay. The finality that the music wants to express becomes for us instead a morbidity. Like watching someone making grand plans without knowing of his imminent death. But we, latecomers, know.

Where in the individual perfection takes place in the twilight of life (Beethoven's last quartets, Bartók's Concerto for Orchestra), in history the epoch's perfection takes place at its zenith. But dawn and dusk are far more exciting than mid day, which, like night, robs us of our shadows.

The melodic rules* of Renaissance polyphony aim to mark a break between the carnal song and the spiritual one. In medieval music, melodies could zig-zag their way (almost) anywhere — just as the tones when we speak are not related to a higher principle, but to the individual words and meaning of the movement. Renaissance polyphony, by contrast, springs not from the tongue or the heart - but from the spirit and thought. Music becomes architecture. Here the keystone is now the worldly meaning of everything, and gravity the master and pattern of everything; in the strictest style the rule is that dissonances may occur only when parts fall, never when they rise.

The remarkable dome of St. Peter's came into being through knowledge that had hitherto lain dormant; legend has it that Michelangelo showed the sceptics the durability of his idea by holding a string between his hands, letting it form an arc, and explaining that every arc the string makes can be turned upwards and describe a shape that will not collapse.

*The most important melodic rule, as we know (besides the obvious ones, such as no dissonant intervals), is: if notes follow each other in ascending order, a larger interval must not follow a smaller one; and vice versa in descending order. (Think of a ball being thrown up in the air and then falling down; shown in still images, laid out in a row.)

One of the rhetorical devices of Renaissance music is the anticipation, where one of the parts takes the lead and anticipates the action. A tension from the unstressed beat is resolved in the next stressed one - or it is extended to end entire sections; the parts are beckoned in one by one; the a-a-amen carried by the waves of the melismas docks, ship after ship, at the port of the keynote. An anticipation, in all its theoretical bloodlessness, is a sign of hope coming true, order out of impending chaos.

In the evolution of note weaving from the Dutch arts to Chopin's ear for the gaps in traditional chords, there was a consensus - what comes before is before what comes after. Forward thinking leads the way of composition.

A dissonance is resolved. A consonance is not resolved.

It takes until modernism for the opposite to appear - so recent in history that the phenomenon has no technical name. Events where the ending is disturbed by some element hanging on into the next section, a lag - (Shostakovich's Eighth String Quartet). It is the world of nightmares; you can clearly see a person getting on the bus, only to meet him seconds later in the hall.

It's a reflection in miniature. A wrong decision, made right by a shift in the world, becomes tradition. A right decision, which through a shift in the world becomes wrong — that is history.

When, towards the end of his life, Schumann revised part of his catalogue in order to satisfy a more classical taste (perhaps this was now also his own), he simply airbrushed out the worst "literary" smells that offended the noses of the new age.

Chopin could never have done so. Chopin never writes programme music. His programme is always the same.With him, the essentially literary never takes on superficial expressions that could have been scrubbed away and washed clean — but reaches to the bottom.

The tone, not the statement. The brushwork, not the motif.

It is said that even as a child, Chopin amused and alarmed those around him with accurate imitations, something he was later able to show in the French salons.

Had Chopin wanted to satisfy the demands of a banal taste for music without literature, he would have had to erase, not revise.

In the century of art music before the full development of the sonata form, the dynamism of the form was given not by a subtle play between forces, main theme and secondary theme, darkness and light, but by the tension between order and chaos. The form of prelude (toccata, fantasia) and fugue stands as a pattern for this tension.

The prelude is ideally (if one can speak of an ideal image of disorder) a fantasia — a piece often entirely without bar lines and tonal values (notes spilled out onto paper) and in which the music, in defiance of everything taught, allows the fingers, the body, the earth, to control the course of events in the place of the head, the mind, the sky.

The fugue's art is heavenly mathematics and earthly engineering combined — a labyrinthine art where neither up nor down, forward nor backward (think of the pieces in Kunst der Fuge that can be played with the notes facing either way up) can exist.

In classicism, chaos is never threatening. It looms in the often almost formless adagio movement like a rainstorm for which there is shelter in the outer movements just after. In Romanticism again, instead, order itself is threatening. The battle is between light and darkness — the outcome is uncertain. Comedy or tragedy.

In the Baroque there is no such possibility of pessimism — order beats chaos as a matter of course. There is no conflict and therefore no real drama — in its place an abyss breaks loose. Above which the world unfolds.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114244763
It's harder than it seems (and it does seem difficult) to get longer/progressive tracks to work in video games. They tend to be hilariously distracting and immersion-breaking whenever there is blatant mismatch with the action or, most insidiously, the lack thereof. At that point you have to design the game around the music rather than the other way around.
Moreover, the prog influence was already fizzling out by the time it was just barely feasible in terms of technical limitations and design repertoire to have a 10+ minute game event that remains interesting throughout.

>>114282823
They didn't need to.
But to try to give a more serious answer, they weren't a "traditional" prog band. They get labeled as progressive rock because, of all the established overarching genre classifications, it's the one that suits them best, but they didn't follow many of the genre's common tropes. Which is why I believe a lot of people are initially turned off by them or have difficulty understanding what they were going for. Most prog bands were interested in epic, escapist, dramatic songwriting, while Gentle Giant's gimmick was creating intricate music puzzles.

>>114286277
Go to a music shop and try out a bunch. Hold them, strum the open strings. put your fingers down on the neck like you know what you're doing, slide your hand up the neck and back down. See how they feel. Don't worry about how they sound. That's not important in the slightest. There's a million things you can do to change how an electric guitar sounds. There's next to nothing you can do to change how it feels. Looks are important too. The most important thing a beginner can do is find a guitar that feels good to hold and look at. You want to give yourself every possible excuse to take your out of the case and pick it up. It'll reduce the chance that you give up after a few weeks like most beginners. You can find tons of cheap guitars online, but you'd hurting your chances of sticking with it by buying one. When starting out, music is goal #2. Goal #1 is not giving up. You can do it anon!

>>114290689
Listen to and play lots of different music from all different genres. Listen actively not passively, really hear all the instruments and what they’re doing, how they interact

Practice learning songs by ear instead of using tabs or tutorial videos

Practice improvising or soloing over music you like (backing tracks are soulless and gay)

Learn more theory, and practice actually applying the theory you learn so it becomes second nature e.g. you shouldn’t have to think about how to solo up and down the neck or where the scales are, you should just know the route naturally, the way you know a footpath in an area you’ve walked many times before

posts.com:
If they could go back to being the band they were on Neighborhoods (2011), I'd be all for it. But given how bad their last single was, it seems like they've gone too far astray.

They started out as basically a skate punk band (Flyswatter to Dude Ranch). Then they became this jokey pop punk band (Enema of the State). But then they became this really interesting alternative rock band with elements of pop punk and post-hardcore (s/t, Neighborhoods, and sort of TOYPAJ). I think the problem is, because Enema was their breakout album and in many people's minds their definitive album, I think blink-182 thinks that's what people want, so they're doing a very hollow imitation of their dumbest period. The problem is, when they did it the first time it was genuinely where they were as artists. Now it's just a moronic style, and it's very pandering. It's not who they are anymore as artists or people, nor could it be - they're pushing 50. If their heart was still in it, they'd be pushing Neighborhoods-type material in darker and weirder directions. But they're doing the opposite of that. As Bowie said, it's dangerous to try and give people what they want - Bowie said his best work was always his most selfish, when he was making music for himself. blink isn't doing anything for themselves as artists, and it doesn't seem like the concept of artistic integrity is even a thought for them, the notion is laughable. They're making shitty dick joke pop punk for drunk middle aged dudes who want to go see them and feel like they're at a college frat party again.

They have some great stuff but I don't see for the life of me how Replacements and Big Star are "cool" while, say, Marshall Crenshaw and The Raspberries aren't. This stuff is all a legacy of when rock music had very arcane, tribal loyalties and the most minor irrelevant shit or even a misconception about a band could have a huge sway on their reputation. Blind leading the blind

I'd bet if Big Star and the Replacements had actually been successful, no one would think they're cool now. Just like Bruce Springsteen or Tom Petty. But because their careers crashed and burned, by complete accident they became a hot commodity within "indie." This isn't what they intended to happen at all, just a lucky by-product of failure due to circumstances beyond their control

I listened to Roman Candle during a shitty time in my life while it was cold and raining outside, and by the time the second song ended I was just on the floor with goosebumps.

It's a hard feeling to describe, only ever had it a couple times in my life, usually when drugs are involved. Like when I was 12 and broke my arm and they gave me morphine- this feeling of "oh shit I really like this, I like this so much it's dangerous. I could do this everyday for as long as I live and abandon all the things I care about if I didn't consciously reject the urge to do so"

And the thing about it is, his music isn't good for anything other than moping around all depressed. I can't listen to it while I'm driving or working out or visiting with people. It has to be alone, maybe with a fifth of liquor in me. And it's absolutely tantalizing then. Like a warm blanket to crawl into. Of course a few of his songs break this mold, and he can cheer you up too ("Say Yes" for example), but most of his top stuff, especially his first 2 albums which imo are his best, those are all made for solitude
